Center: Russian Nuclear Structure and Reaction Data Centre, Kurchatov Institute, Moscow, Russia
title: Alpha induced fission of Bi-209.

x4freetext: Alpha induced fission of Bi-209.
Abstract:  the alpha induced fission of 209-Bi has been
carried out at alpha energy of 49.1 MeV and 44.9 MeV
using gamma ray spectrometry. The cross sections for
The  production of ten fission products at alpha energy
of 49.1 MeV and four fission products at alpha energy
of 44.9 MeV have been determined. The mass
distribution has been found to be broad with peak  near
mass  103.   The  cross  section  for the production of
22-Na, 24-Na and 28-Mg in the alpha  induced  reaction
of 27-Al has been determined at 49.6 MeV and 45.4 MeV.

x4codes.hlp: Bhabha Atomic Research Centre (BARC), Trombay, Mumbai, India

x4freetext: Radiochemistry Division
The targets of super pure 209-Bi were prepared by
vacuum evaporation on 25.4 mum super pure aluminium
foil. The targets of 2 mg/cm**2 of bismuth were used
for irradiation.  In order to avoid the cross
contamination of fission products due to large activity
of direct reaction products, the 209-Bi target was
Covered with a 0.76 mumeter super pure aluminium foil.
This will allow the fission products to pass and will
prevent the reaction products. The whole assembly was
put in a target holder and irradiated for a suitable
length of time with a 50 MeV alpha particle beam of 2 -
3 muA. The Incident alpha energy on the first bismuth
target was 49.1 MeV where as on the second bismuth
target it was 44.9 MeV.
The bismuth targets and aluminium catchers were
separated from each other carefully to avoid cross
contamination.  The aluminium catchers were mounted
separately on perspex plates in suitable geometry.

x4codes.hlp: Variable Energy Cyclotron Centre, Kolkata, India

x4freetext: Three irradiations were carried out for
30, 30 and 63 minutes.
In each irradiation the decay of the gamma ray
peak of the fission products and reaction products in
the aluminium catchers were followed for suitable lenth
of time
Correction in code of Institute  was made,
according N.Otsuka comment
The errors listed are the standard deviations
between the results from different irradiations and
various gamma rays
